{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fa8228ac-24ef-41ec-9590-213206ff6722","content":"In .NET MAUI, those methods moved from `Application` to `Window`. You have two options:\n\n**1. Override lifecycle methods on a custom Window:**\n\n```csharp\npublic class MyWindow : Window\n{\n    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }\n\n    protected override void OnCreated()    { /* OnStart equivalent */ }\n    protected override void OnDeactivated() { /* OnSleep equivalent */ }\n    protected override void OnResumed()    { /* OnResume equivalent */ }\n}\n```\n\nThen in your `App` class:\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n    => new MyWindow(new MainPage());\n```\n\n**2. Subscribe to events inline:**\n\n```csharp\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = new Window(new MainPage());\n    window.Created     += (s, e) => { /* OnStart */ };\n    window.Deactivated += (s, e) => { /* OnSleep */ };\n    window.Resumed     += (s, e) => { /* OnResume */ };\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\n**Key mappings:**\n| Xamarin.Forms | MAUI Window |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart` | `OnCreated` / `Created` |\n| `OnSleep` | `OnDeactivated` / `Deactivated` |\n| `OnResume` | `OnResumed` / `Resumed` |\n\nThere's also `OnStopped`, `OnActivated`, and `OnDestroying` for more granular control.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"62c1e7a8-ceb5-401c-a3af-9f7ba274f3fd","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a straightforward knowledge question about the MAUI lifecycle API.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, and `OnResume` in your `Application` class. In .NET MAUI, the lifecycle model changed significantly. The equivalent approach uses the `Window` lifecycle events or the `ILifecycleEventHandler` pattern.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the `Application` class no longer has `OnStart`, `OnSleep`, `OnResume` virtual methods. \n\nInstead, you work with `Window` lifecycle events—you can subscribe to `Window.Created`, `Window.Stopped`/`Window.Deactivated`, and `Window.Resumed` events that map to the old lifecycle stages, or override the corresponding methods like `OnCreated()`, `OnStopped()`/`OnDeactivated()`, and `OnResumed()` on a custom `Window` subclass. equivalent to the Xamarin.Forms lifecycle events, and I can implement them either by subclassing `Window` and overriding the methods, or by subscribing to the corresponding events in the `CreateWindow` method.","outputTokens":922,"requestId":"503B:28231D:1C6129A:1F67864:69FA90B1"},"id":"ba9284ed-503c-41d6-9937-19034a1903fe","timestamp":"2026-05-06T00:52:17.098Z","parentId":"8eef03b3-e6d5-4e53-9840-9ddf0863dc0b"}
